-- Japan, China, India, Malaysia, Philippines: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview
-- Anil Varma
-- 2010-07-06T22:26:05Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-06/japan-china-india-malaysia-philippines-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold a
media briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 The Ministry of Finance will release at 8:50 a.m. its
report on the nation’s official reserve assets for June.  
 The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due June 2020
was 1.13 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 87.58 per dollar at 7:13 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: The finance ministry plans to sell 28 billion yuan
($4.1 billion) of five-year debt.  
 The yield on the 2.53 percent note due in June 2015 was
2.57 percent. The yuan was at 6.7801 per dollar.  
 India: The government plans to raise as much as 35 billion
rupees ($748 million) selling treasury bills. It will offer 20
billion rupees of 91-day bills and 15 billion rupees of 182-day
notes, according to the central bank.  
 The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.61
percent. The rupee was at 46.905.  
 Malaysia: The central bank plans to sell 1.5 billion
ringgit ($468 million) of 91-day fixed-income securities and 1
billion ringgit of 61-day Islamic debt.  
 The yield on the 3.835 percent debt maturing in August 2015
was 3.49 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit was
at 3.206.  
 Philippines: The central bank will release details of end-
June foreign reserves and bank lending in May. The reserves
stood at a record $47.7 billion at the end of May and lending
rose 6.2 percent in April from a year earlier.  
 The yield on the 7.75 percent debt due February 2020 was
7.88 percent, according to Philippine Dealing & Exchange Corp.
The peso was at 46.38.  
